\pard\f0\fs28\qc {\b 40.          Salvia}               L.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc By I.C. Hedge.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Herbs or shrubs. Flowers in axillary verticillasters (rarely cymes). Calyx 2-lipped, the teeth unequal; lower lip deeply 2-fid or -dentate; upper lip 3-dentate, rarely subentire. Corolla 2-lipped; upper lip straight or falcate; lower lip 3-lobed, the middle lobe the largest; tube straight or invaginated, with or without a ring of hairs inside. Stamens 2; connective usually articulating with the filament, one arm with a fertile cell, the other more or less sterile, often expanded and flattened distally (dolabriform).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  Most species grow on stony slopes or roadsides, in dry grassland, cultivated ground or similar habitats, and if no ecological information is given in the text a habitat of this type is to be presumed.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  Many non-European species are cultivated for ornament.
